<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp1sec2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The order of the integers</title>

  <p> </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-definition-order">
    <title>Order</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A set <m>X</m> has a <term>(total) order</term> if there is a binary relationship <m>\le</m> satisfying: 
            <dl width="narrow">
              <li><title>(O1)</title>
                <p>
                  (<term>reflexivity</term>.) If <m>a\in X</m>, then <m>a\le a </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(O2)</title>
                <p>
                  (<term>transitivity</term>.) If <m>a,b,c \in X</m> satisfy <m>a\le b</m> and <m>b\le c</m>, then <m>a \le c</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(O3)</title>
                <p>
                  (<term>symmetry</term>.) If <m>a,b \in X</m> satisfy <m>a\le b</m> and <m>b\le a</m>, then <m>a=b</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(O4)</title>
                <p>
                  (<term>totality</term>.) If <m>a,b \in X</m>, then one of the following hold: <m>a\le b</m> or <m>b\le a</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>



  <definition xml:id="definition-ordered-ring">
    <title>Ordered Ring</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A ring <m>R</m> is an <term>ordered ring</term> if <m>R</m> has a (total) order that is compatible with its operations by satisfying: 
            <dl width="narrow">
               <li><title>(OR1)</title>
                <p>
                  (<term>translation</term>.) If <m>a,b,c \in R</m> and <m>a\le b</m>, then <m>a +c\le b+c</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(OR2)</title>
                <p>
                  (<term>scaling</term>.) If <m>a,b \in R</m> satisfy <m>0 \le a</m> and <m>0 \le b</m>, then <m>0\le ab</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
  Observe the symbols <m>\le</m>, <m>\ge</m>, <m>&lt;</m>, and <m>&gt;</m> will all be used in the usual ways.
</p>
  
  <p>
    We call elements of an ordered ring <term> positive </term> if it is greater than zero and <term> negative </term> if it is less than zero.
  </p>


<proposition xml:id="prop-01">
  <title></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is an ordered ring and <m> a \in R </m> is positive (resp. negative), then <m>-a</m> is negative (resp. positive).  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a proof by cases. For each case, do a direct proof.  In the first case, suppose <m> 0 &lt; a </m>.  Show <m> -a &lt; 0 </m> (why???).  Now do the other case.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>  and <xref ref="definition-ordered-ring"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<proposition xml:id="prop-1_2-055">
  <title></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a ordered ring and <m>a,b,c\in R</m> are positive such that  <m>a</m> is (multiplicatively) invertible and <m>0&lt;b&lt;c</m>, then <m>0&lt;ab&lt;ac</m>.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a proof by contradiction.  We know it must be the case that <m>0 \le ab \le ac</m> (why???) but what could go wrong and how to we show those things cannot happen? Suppose one of the undesirable things happened and how does the invertibility of <m>a</m> lead to a contradiction?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-ordered-ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-well-ordered"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>




<definition xml:id="definition-well-ordered">
  <title>Well-Ordered Set</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>X</m> is a set with a total order, it is <term>well-ordered</term> if every <em>non-empty</em> subset contains a <term>minimal element</term>, i.e. in symbols, if <m>S\subset X</m> is <em>non-empty</em>, then there exists an element <m>a\in S</m> such that, for all <m>b\in S</m>  it is the case that <m>a\le b</m>. 
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p> 
  Note that to invoke well-ordering, we must certify the set in question is <em>non-empty</em>.
</p>

<proposition xml:id="prop-1_2-05">
  <title></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a ordered ring whose positive elements are well-ordered, then the minimal positive element, <m>e</m> is (multiplicatively) invertible.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Let <m>e</m> denote the minimal positive element of <m>R</m>.  (Why does <m>e</m> exist???) If <m>e=1</m>, we are done (why???).  Otherwise <m>0&lt; e &lt; 1</m>.  Look at the set 
      <me>
        S = \{1-ke >0 \mid k \in \Z \}
      </me> 
      <m>S</m> is nonempty (why???).  There exists a minimal element <m>1-ne\in S</m>.  With minimality in mind, can <m>1-ne&gt; e</m>? Can <m>1-ne&lt; e</m>? Show  <m>1-ne=e</m> (why???).  Use this to find an element <m>m\in \Z</m> such that <m>me=1</m> (how???).  You may find  <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-ordered-ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-well-ordered"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>



<proposition xml:id="prop-03">
  <title></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a ordered ring whose positive elements are well-ordered, then the minimal positive element is 1.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a proof by contradiction.  Let <m>e</m> denote the minimal positive element of <m>R</m> and suppose <m>0 &lt; e &lt; 1</m>.  What happens when you multiply by <m>e</m>?  Can you find a contradiction?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>,  <xref ref="definition-ordered-ring"/>,  <xref ref="definition-ordered-ring"/>, <xref ref="prop-1_2-055"/> <xref ref="prop-1_2-05"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<proposition xml:id="prop-04">
  <title></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a ordered ring whose positive elements are well-ordered, and <m>a,b \in R</m> satisfy <m>0 &lt; a</m> and <m>0 &lt; b</m>, then <m>0
        &lt; ab</m>.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      ggg
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<proposition xml:id="prop-08">
  <title>Well-Ordered Rings are Domains</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a ordered ring whose positive elements are well-ordered, and <m>a,b \in R</m> satisfy <m>ab=0</m>, then either <m>a=0</m> or <m>b = 0</m>.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      ggg
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<proposition xml:id="prop-06">
  <title>Well-Ordered Rings Have Cancellation</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a ordered ring whose positive elements are well-ordered, and <m>a,b,c \in R</m> satisfy <m>ab=ac</m>, then either <m>a=0</m> or <m>b = c</m>.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      ggg
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<p> The integers, <m>\Z</m> are in fact the <em>unique </em> ordered commutative ring with identity whose positive elements are well-ordered.  Going forward we will simply refer to this set as the integers and all properties of the integers will follow from these.
</p>

</section>